autodromo_vbf_el_pinar;1eb.name: Autodromo Victor Borrat Fabini - Circuito 1 con Extension y curva Beco Passadore
autodromo_vbf_el_pinar;1eb.description: The Autódromo Víctor Borrat Fabini at El Pinar - named in honour of the local racing great who was instrumental in its construction - is Uruguay's most important racing circuit and the home of AUVO, (Asociación Uruguaya de Volantes), the national racing association. Active throughout the year with a busy calendar of events, the circuit has recently been extended, providing racers with a new combination of corners for the first time since the mid-1970s. The circuit is located in the Department of Canelones, around 30 km east of the Uruguayan capital, Montevideo. This close proximity has been one of the secrets of its ongoing success, alongside its favourable location relative to Argentina and Brazil, whose major series have paid visits on numerous occasions, boosting El Pinar's importance as a regional racing hub. The circuit was built in 1956, opening in October of that year, meaning that AUVO was one of the few private institutions in South America to own and operate its own racing facility. In its original form it was triangular in outline, with a series of infield twists and turns adding variety to the rear of the paddock area. The perimeter course measured just over 1.6 miles  ===================================================  El Autódromo Víctor Borrat Fabini en El Pinar, nombrado en honor al gran piloto local que jugó un papel decisivo en su construcción, es el circuito de carreras más importante de Uruguay y el hogar de AUVO, (Asociación Uruguaya de Volantes), la asociación nacional de carreras. Activo durante todo el año con un ajetreado calendario de eventos, el circuito se ha ampliado recientemente, proporcionando a los corredores una nueva combinación de curvas por primera vez desde mediados de la década de 1970. El circuito está ubicado en el Departamento de Canelones, a unos 30 km al este de la capital uruguaya, Montevideo. Esta proximidad ha sido uno de los secretos de su éxito continuo, junto con su ubicación favorable en relación con Argentina y Brasil, cuyas principales series han visitado el autódromo en numerosas ocasiones, aumentando la importancia de El Pinar como un centro regional de carreras. El circuito se construyó en 1956 y se inauguró en octubre de ese año, lo que significa que AUVO fue una de las pocas instituciones privadas en América del Sur en poseer y operar su propia instalación de carreras. En su forma original, tenía un contorno triangular, con una serie de giros y curvas en el interior del perímetro, que agregaban variedad a la parte trasera del área del paddock. El recorrido del perímetro medía poco más de 2,5 kilómetros.
autodromo_vbf_el_pinar;1eb.author: MIntruso Custom Shop

autumnring;autumnringlarge.name: Autumn Ring - Forward Layout
autumnring;autumnringlarge.description: Autumn Ring is a course characteristically set in the early Fall/Autumn season and is the only course in the entire series that is. Despite this, the track is entirely clear of fallen foliage such as leaves and twigs, and much of the area remains full of lush color, giving a relatively unique blend of green and red-orange coloration. Being the premier full circuit of the complex, The course itself is a road course, spanning a decent length of 2.95km (1.83 miles), and a wrought blend of tight corners both smooth and sharp. It is among one of the shortest full-length road courses in the games, but with the slower nature of its corners and shorter straight sections, one would be hard-pressed to find lap times not comparable to other, longer, more high-speed circuits in the series.

avus_dtm;normal.name: Avus DTM
avus_dtm;normal.description: Berlin 90s. Short layout with chicane. Three spots with less grip!                   Background information:      The Avus is a public highway on the outskirts of Berlin.     The track layout shows the race track at the beginning of the 1990s.     The track length is 2.639 km and has a long straight followed by the south curve of a double chicane and the northern curve.     The best opportunities overhaul there are in the south curve (which also often ends in a crash) and the northern curve (when the opponent was too fast and the inside lane to overtake releases).      An old video for fun, one lap from Gerd Ruch Onboard AVUS DTM 95:     https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WmQiMzE5NNE      A nice 45mins video report from an Avus DTM race 1995, feat. Bernd Schneider, Jan Magnussen, Kurt Thim, Alexander Grau, Alessandro Nannini, Ellen Lohr:     https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1274&v=4Elw6lde2YA      GTR2 conversion to Assetto Corsa 2019 july 20 by leBluem, permission by derDummeKlemmer, F1-Edition      Original credits:  (see readme(s) for details)      Avus/Berlin for GTL by Andre F1-Edition      The track layout is from Peter Kuhn with approval by Alfredo Martinez.     Some 3D objects such as the Funkturm, the Mercedes-tower, including the main grandstand were placed with the permission of Jimi-46.     The GTR2-track has been reworked by ZWISS, see also Readme_for_GTR2, thank you for this work.     F1-Edition converted the track to GTL and had 3DOs, textures and AIW reworked or renewed.

rmi_siracusa_2021;rmi_siracusa_2021.name: Siracusa 2021
rmi_siracusa_2021;rmi_siracusa_2021.description: Located in Eastern Sicily, the small circuit of Autodromo International Siracusa is left as a shadow of its former, more prestigious self. Originally a street circuit, racing began in Spring 1950 when the circuit held the 1st Coppa d'Oro di Sicilia (Sicily Golden Cup), a race for Sport cars. The following year the circuit held the first Syracuse Grand Prix, a non championship F1 race. The circuit continued to host F1 races until 1967, with racing coming to an end in 1970.  By 2000, a new permanent circuit was built and small racing events were held.  Recently, this circuit fell out of use and is now abandonned.

rt_bathurst;rt_bathurst.description: Laser Scanned ACC Conversion.Mount Panorama Circuit is a motor racing track located in Bathurst, New South Wales, Australia. It is situated on a hill with the dual official names of Mount Panorama and Wahluu and is best known as the home of the Bathurst 12 Hour event held each February. The track is 6.213 km (3.861 mi) in length, and is technically a street circuit, and is a public road, with normal speed restrictions when no racing events are being run.The track has an unusual design by modern standards, with a 174-metre (571 ft) vertical difference between its highest and lowest points, and grades as steep as 1:6.13.

trialmountain;forward.name: Trial Mountain - Forward Layout
trialmountain;forward.description: The Trial Mountain Circuit is a fictional circuit that has appeared in all mainline versions of Gran Turismo except Gran Turismo Sport, and has also featured in Tourist Trophy and Gran Turismo PSP. It is a almost 4 kilometres circuit run on tarmac which appears to be set in a forest clearing within a mountainous area. The circuit features several blind corners, three tunnels, a long, uphill back straight and a series of fast compound corners. It is seen by most players as one of the easiest circuits in the Gran Turismo Series. That is, one of the easiest to drive and memorize. However, it is one of the hardest circuits to drive fast due to the length of the circuit.
